        "text": "### Chemistry Insights\n\n1. **Fe³⁺ binds most strongly** (log K ≈ 28), which is why DTPA is widely used as an industrial iron sequestrant in pulp bleaching and water treatment. The enormous ~12 log-unit gap between Fe³⁺ and Fe²⁺ reflects the much higher charge density of the ferric ion.\n\n2. **Lanthanides cluster tightly** around log K ≈ 21–23, making DTPA the backbone of the classic MRI contrast agent **Gd-DTPA (Magnevist®)**. The high thermodynamic stability ensures the toxic Gd³⁺ ion stays chelated *in vivo*.\n\n3. DTPA generally exceeds EDTA by **2–3 log K units** for most metals, thanks to its additional fifth carboxylate arm providing an extra coordination site — a textbook example of the chelate effect amplified by denticity.\n\nIf you'd like to drill into a **specific metal** (e.g., detailed conditions, protonated species MHL, or hydroxo complexes), just let me know!\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (SRD-46)*",
